<br>
Despite that huge, sloppy ball of bullshit noted above, EQ is a fun game. EQ is fun in spite of itself. Whether you like the game or not, DAoC was a very good thing for EQ. Most of the radical gameplay changes in the last 6 months are directly due to that game going live and proving that, yes, it's okay for melee to be able to bind themselves, and yes, it's okay for a game to have almost no downtime, and yes, it's okay for casters to never have to stare at a spellbook for hours at a time. Competition bred those changes, and it bred this new price hike as well. In five years, new MMOGs are going to cost 30 bucks a month to play, and people will pay it. And you'll be getting a deal with your 15 bucks a month spent on EQ. <br>
<br>
You have to remember that the game is a business, and that business is primarily concerned with the bottom line. They'll do what they need to do to sweeten the deal for you, the consumer, so they can continue to rake in the dough. The idealists who brought us &quot;the vision&quot; are all gone. This is not a bad thing for EverQuest. Pay or don't pay, the game will prosper with or without the few thousand people disgruntled by both the EQ price hike and the new $0.37 postage stamp. <br>
<br>
